as it turns out, the form produces errors, and at least one of the errors has a complex object inside, which introduces recursion into the json encoding process*: 

            return $this-&gt;json([
                &quot;status&quot; =&gt; &quot;error(s)&quot;,
                &quot;errors&quot; =&gt; $form-&gt;getErrors(true, true)
            ], 200);

to prevent this from happening, it&#39;s preferable to prepare the errors to be shown:
```
$formerrors = [];
foreach($form-&gt;getErrors(true, true) as $error) {
    $fieldname = ($origin = $error-&gt;getOrigin()) ? $origin-&gt;getName() : null;
    if($fieldname) {
        $formerrors[$fieldname] = $error-&gt;getMessage();
    } else {
        $formerrors[] = $error-&gt;getMessage();
}
return $this-&gt;json([
    &quot;status&quot; =&gt; &quot;error(s)&quot;,
    &quot;errors&quot; =&gt; $formerrors,
], 200);
```
since an error can have *no* origin but the form itself, the condition in the loop *might* be necessary. also: for deep nested forms, it might be necessary to improve the approach.

As a side note: the returned status code (`200` in your case) is not okay and it should be something in the 400s, since the request produced error, the response should not be 200 (&quot;OK&quot;). 


*) for anyone wondering how to notice: it usually ALL of the 30s standard execution time until a timeout occurs. and if the standard execution time is set to be unlimited, the whole computer may freeze because it slowly eats up all the memory to prepare an infinitely long answer. this almost always happens when `var_dump`ing or `print_r`ing complex objects that in their references (possible multiple layers deep) reference the complex objects or each other, creating an infinite loop as the serialization process follows references deeper into the objects. `dump` as well as `dd` (symfony debug output) will usually perform *way* better (recursion is avoided) and thus allow inspection of the object.

